Why do API Testing?
Faster execution
Earlier defect detection
Independent of UI
Better coverage of business logic

For a manual tester transitioning to Playwright, the next topics to learn after these basics are:

Authentication (Bearer tokens, OAuth, JWT)
Query parameters and path parameters
Request/response validation
API chaining (using data from one API in another)
Playwright's APIRequestContext
Mocking API responses in Playwright

These six topics cover most API questions asked in automation testing interviews.

What is REST API?

An API that uses HTTP methods (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE) to perform operations on resources.

Difference between PUT and PATCH?
PUT → Updates the entire resource.
PATCH → Updates only specified fields.
Difference between 401 and 403?
401 → Not authenticated.
403 → Authenticated but not authorized.
Difference between API Testing and UI Testing?

API Testing         	UI Testing
Faster	                Slower
No browser needed	    Browser required
Tests backend logic	    Tests end-to-end flow
More stable	            More prone to UI changes


import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('Get User', async ({ request }) => {

    const response = await request.get(
        'https://reqres.in/api/users/2'
    );

    expect(response.status()).toBe(200);

    const body = await response.json();

    expect(body.data.id).toBe(2);
});


